Beroaldus (in Mo.) seems to take situ nidoris as meaning ‘with reale of stench.' Beroaldus quotes Donatus on Aeneid vii 440 ‘uicta situ uerique effeta senectus' where he says that situs is corruptio ex umore et diuturnitate contracta and that the word was also applied to a musty smell. But it is obvious that the action of umor is not necessarily implied in the word. nidor is used of various smells, cf. Juv. v 162 ‘nidor culinae'3 Lucr. vi 792 of a candle blown out3 Livy xxxviii 7, 13 of burning feathers.
